{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490993"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:26:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:26:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"797"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/797"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.07,0.68,0.23,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"797"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54361"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/797"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"797"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39870"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"5602"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35796"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54361"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man is admitted for a cystoscopy following an episode of frank haematuria. He has a medical history of emphysema, with multiple hospital admissions for infective exacerbations of COPD in the past year. His medications include a regular fluticasone/umeclidinium/vilanterol inhaler. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history. He is only able to walk 100m before needing to stop for breath. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately reflects this patient\u0027s American Society of Anaesthesiologists (ASA) score?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["ASA I","ASA II","ASA III","ASA IV","ASA V"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe American Society of Anaesthesiologists has designed a scoring system which defines the risk of a particular individual who is being planned for a surgical procedure:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA I\u003C/strong\u003E A normal healthy patient\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA II\u003C/strong\u003E A patient with mild systemic disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA III\u003C/strong\u003E A patient with severe systemic disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA IV\u003C/strong\u003E A patient with severe systemic disease that is a constant threat to life\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA V\u003C/strong\u003E A moribund patient who is not expected to survive without the operation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA VI\u003C/strong\u003E A declared brain-dead patient whose organs are to be removed for donor purposes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u0027E\u0027 can be added to each score, denoting an emergency, where any delay in surgical treatment would lead to a substantial increase in the threat to life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ASA lists poorly controlled systemic diseases such as COPD, diabetes, and obesity as examples warranting a score of ASA III.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, examples of ASA IV include sepsis, recent AMI (\u0026lt;3 months), DIC, or ESRF not receiving dialysis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is much subjectivity surrounding ASA classifications due to differing opinions between anaesthetists on what constitutes a \u0022mild\u0022 vs \u0022severe\u0022 vs \u0022life-threatening\u0022 disease, as well as many localised diseases (e.g. MI) causing systemic effects. Despite this variability, there is a strong correlation between ASA scoring and postoperative complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with a single poorly controlled disease fit the criteria for ASA III."],"references":["Daabiss M. American Society of Anaesthesiologists physical status classification. Indian J Anaesth. 2011;55(2):111-115. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3106380/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39870"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"797"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39870"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T14:57:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-04T14:58:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"797"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54361"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relations